Profiles, and externalised configuration.

A real application needs different wiring in different environments. You want a real database in production, an in-memory one in your tests, and maybe a stub for local development. Spring's tool for this is the at-profile annotation, which tags a bean with the environment it belongs to. So you can have one at-bean method for the production data source, marked profile prod, and another for an embedded data source, marked profile not-prod, meaning it is active in every environment except production. You choose the active profile by setting the property spring-profiles-active, either in a properties file, as an environment variable, or with a command-line flag. Only the beans whose profile matches the active set ever get registered.

The related idea is externalised configuration. Hard-coding values directly into your Java is a smell, because the same code should run in dev, staging, and production with different values. Spring reads configuration from many sources, properties files, yaml, environment variables, command-line flags, and it exposes that configuration to you in three ways. At-value injects a single property, and you can give it a default. The environment object lets you look properties up programmatically in code. And at-configuration-properties binds a whole group of related keys, under a shared prefix, to a typed record.

Of those three, at-configuration-properties is the right default. It groups related properties under a prefix, it binds them to a strongly-typed record, it can validate them at startup so a misconfiguration fails fast, and it gives you real autocomplete support in your I-D-E. Reach for at-value only for genuine one-off cases.
